idea: think of ε as a family of elliptic curves (this is what we call an "algebraic family") and study the behavior of the fibers (which are elliptic curves)

this surface ε is what we call an "elliptic surface" and since it's born from an elliptic curve, it always comes with this morphism f and with a section C->ε taking t to the corresponding O_t point (neutral element of E_t).

and indeed for almost any point t we can look at the fiber f⁻¹(t) (the points on ε whose image under f is t) and that is exactly the same that evaluating A and B at some point t, so it's an elliptic curve E_t parametrized by t !!

i gonna call this subvariety ε and since it's contained in P²\times C i can take the second projection which yields a morphism f: ε->C taking ([X,Y,Z],t) to t. This exactly the same we do when studying base change on schemes!

if you decide *not* to evaluate A and B in some point t, you are introducing a new variable, so you are looking at something of higher dimension (2-dim), namely a subvariety of P²\times C consisting of the points ([X,Y,Z],t) where X,Y,Z are the homogeneous coordinates of E...
if you evaluate A and B at some point t of C you get (almost always) an elliptic curve parametrized by that point t... which sounds very familiar to the concept of fiber right 🤔
